Mortgage Probability of Default & Fraud Detection Project¶

Author: Huizhe (Sunny) ZHU - hz2657

Steps

  1. clean data, match column names and description

  2. feature selection by correlation matrix and decision tree

  3. EDA

  4. fit model and make prediction

  5. model evaluation: ROC, gains table

2.1 correlation matrix¶

Correlation states how the features are related to each other or the target variable. It can be positive (increase in one value of feature increases the value of the target variable) or negative (increase in one value of feature decreases the value of the target variable)

In [544]:
# get correlations of each features in dataset
corr = df1.corr()
In [142]:
# drop AP006 from df1 because it is not contained in correlation matrix 
df1 = df1.drop(columns=['AP006'])

We remove one of two features that have a correlation higher than 0.9

In [545]:
# remove one of two features that have a correlation higher than 0.9
columns = np.full((corr.shape[0],), True, dtype=bool)

for i in range(corr.shape[0]):
    for j in range(i+1, corr.shape[0]):
        if corr.iloc[i,j] >= 0.9:
            if columns[j]:
                columns[j] = False
                
selected_columns = df1.columns[columns]
df3 = df1[selected_columns]
In [546]:
# add AP006 back in the new dataset df3
df3['AP006'] = df.loc[:,'AP006']

2.2.2 deal with missing values¶

before feature selection by decision tree, we need to deal with missing values

  • to run decision tree model first, we impute na first
  • reference: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/impute.html#impute
In [549]:
# we replace missing values by mean values for the purpose of feature selection 
X_train=X_train.fillna(X_train.mean())

2.2.3 simple decision tree for variable selection¶

Decision tree algorithms such as classification and regression trees (CART) offer importance scores based on the reduction in the criterion used to select split points, like Gini or entropy.

We can use the CART algorithm for feature importance implemented in scikit-learn as the DecisionTreeRegressor and DecisionTreeClassifier classes.

In [552]:
# decision tree for feature importance on a classification problem
from sklearn.datasets import make_classification
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from matplotlib import pyplot

# convert AP006 into numeric 
X_train=pd.get_dummies(X_train, columns=['AP006'])
# define dataset
X = X_train
y = y_train
# define the model
model = DecisionTreeClassifier()
# fit the model
model.fit(X, y)
# get importance
importance = model.feature_importances_

# plot feature importance
pyplot.bar([x for x in range(len(importance))], importance)
pyplot.show()

3.1 deal with NA, and '-99', '-98', '-1' values¶

for na values:

  • 'PA022', 'PA028', 'PA029', 'PA031', 'CD008', 'CD018', 'CD071', 'CD072', 'CD088', 'CD100', 'CD113', 'CD115', 'CD130', 'CD131', 'CD152', 'CD153', 'CD160', 'CD166', 'CD169' has 185 NA values, MB005 has 1391 NA values

for abnormal values:

  • PA022 has 788 values for -99, PA028,PA029,PA031 has 25359 '-98' and 788 '-99'
  • PA022 also has 25359 values for '-1'
  • CD008,CD018,CD071,CD072,CD088,CD100,CD113...CD160 has 1692 '-99'

these values are likely NAs from different, so we default the "-99", "-98", "-1" to NaN

3.2 Binning numeric variables¶

# first we combine x_train and y_train
train_data = X_train

In [558]:
# write a function, loop through, to create binning variables for selected features
def binning(var,df):
    df[var + '_bin'] = pd.qcut(df[var],10,duplicates='drop').values.add_categories("NoData").astype(str)
    df[var + '_bin'] = df[var + '_bin'].fillna("NoData")
    df[var + '_bin'].value_counts(dropna=False)
 
# PA028: AVG_LEN_COLLECTION_OR_HIGH_RISK_CALLS
features = ['PA022','PA028', 'PA029', 'PA031', 'CD008', 'CD018', 'CD071', 'CD072', 'CD088', 'CD100', 'CD113', 'CD115', 'CD130', 'CD131', 'CD152', 'CD153', 'CD160', 'CD166', 'CD169']

for i in features:
    binning(i,train_data)

def plot_X_and_Y(var):

4. model prediction¶

We use logistic model to make prediction.

assumption of logistic model:

  • data is linearly (or curvy linearly) separable in space.
  • no outliers in data, cuz Logistic regression will push the decision boundary towards the outlier.
  • no high correlations (multicollinearity) among the predictors, which we take care of at the beginning by correlation matrix

dicision tree

  • Decision Trees are non-linear classifiers

5.4 Cumulative Lift¶

  • Lift is a measure of the effectiveness of a predictive model calculated as the ratio between the results obtained with and without the predictive model.
  • from the graph we can see, we are 1.8 times more likely to capture a default as if we use no model.
In [590]:
def gains_table(Y_test,y_pred):
    df_prep = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['actual','pred'])
    df_prep['actual'] = Y_test
    df_prep['pred'] =y_pred
    df_prep = df_prep.sort_values(by='pred',ascending=False)
    df_prep['row_id'] = range(0,0+len(df_prep))
    df_prep.head()

    df_prep['decile'] = (df_prep['row_id'] / (len(df_prep)/10)).astype(int)
    df_prep.loc[df_prep['decile'] == 10] =9
    df_prep['decile'].value_counts()

    # Create gains table
    gains = df_prep.groupby('decile')['actual'].agg(['count','sum'])
    gains.columns = ['count','actual']
    gains

    gains['non_actual'] = gains['count'] - gains['actual']
    gains['cum_count'] = gains['count'].cumsum()
    gains['cum_actual'] = gains['actual'].cumsum()
    gains['cum_non_actual'] = gains['non_actual'].cumsum()
    gains['percent_cum_actual'] = (gains['cum_actual'] / np.max(gains['cum_actual'])).round(2)
    gains['percent_cum_non_actual'] = (gains['cum_non_actual'] / np.max(gains['cum_non_actual'])).round(2)
    gains['if_random'] = np.max(gains['cum_actual']) /10
    gains['if_random'] = gains['if_random'].cumsum()
    gains['lift'] = (gains['cum_actual'] / gains['if_random']).round(2)
    gains['K_S'] = np.abs( gains['percent_cum_actual'] - gains['percent_cum_non_actual']  ) * 100 
    gains['gain'] = (gains['cum_actual'] / gains['cum_count']*100).round(2)
    return(gains)
    
gains = gains_table(y_test,y_pred)
gains
gains['lift'].plot.line()
